rd locals who refuse to give up as they try to transform Flint into a smaller, greener town that offers lessons for cities all over the world. Hard-hitting, insightful, and often painfully funny, Teardown reminds us that cities are ultimately defined by people, not politics or economics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aabandoned houses.  abiography.  abiology.  abusiness.  acareer.  acheap houses.  acities.  acity life.  acity living.  acrowded cities.  acultural studies.  adangerous cities.  adefiant homeowners.  adetroit.  aeconomics.  aengaging.  aflint.  ahistorical.  ahistory.  ahousing.  ainterviews.  amichigan authors.  amichigan.  amoney.  aoral history.  apage turner.  apersonal memoir.  apersonal quest.  apreservation.  arealistic.  arust belt.  asocial history.  asocial justice.  asocial science.  asociological science.  asociology.  aurban america.  aurban homesteaders.  aurban planning.  aurban.  aurbanism.  awealth.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052027052740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095537040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520955370423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520955370/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY